    "summary": "Nevali Cori was a Pre-Pottery Neolithic settlement in southeastern Anatolia, situated on a tributary of the Euphrates River near the modern town of Hilvan in Turkey. Occupied from approximately 8600 to 8000 BCE, the site was excavated in the 1980s and early 1990s before it too was inundated by the Ataturk Dam reservoir. Nevali Cori is important for its evidence of early monumental architecture and sophisticated sculptural art that place it in the same cultural tradition as the nearby site of [[event:3|Gobekli Tepe]].\n\nThe most significant architectural feature at Nevali Cori was a special-purpose building interpreted as a cult or communal assembly structure, containing T-shaped limestone pillars with relief carvings of human arms and hands as well as animal and bird motifs. These pillars are stylistically related to those at Gobekli Tepe and [[event:1390|Karahan Tepe]], forming part of a broader tradition of monumental pillar architecture in upper Mesopotamia during the Pre-Pottery Neolithic. Sculptures recovered from Nevali Cori include a remarkable carved limestone human head and a totem-like sculpture combining human and bird features, representing some of the earliest figurative sculpture in the region.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neval%C4%B1_%C3%87ori",
